# Verbs Reference Content

Verb conjugation patterns and the system behind Greek verbs.

## Purpose

Explain the conjugation SYSTEM - learn 3 patterns, conjugate thousands of verbs. Verb vocabulary browsing is at /learn/verbs.

## Key Insight

Greek verb endings show who's doing the action, so you often don't need separate pronouns. Learn three patterns and conjugate thousands of verbs.

---

## Voice: Who Does the Action?

<section name="voice-explanation">
<title>Greek verbs show not just WHO (the endings) but also the DIRECTION of action</title>

### Active: Subject DOES the action
- βλέπω τον φίλο = I see the friend
- Action flows FROM me TO the friend

### Passive: Subject RECEIVES the action
- βλέπομαι από τον φίλο = I am seen by the friend
- Action flows TO me FROM the friend

### The -μαι Marker
The -μαι ending is the passive marker:
- βλέπω (I see) → βλέπομαι (I am seen)
- ακούω (I hear) → ακούομαι (I am heard)

### Deponent: Passive form, active meaning
Some verbs ONLY exist in -μαι form, but their meaning is active:
- έρχομαι = I come (not "I am come-d")
- θυμάμαι = I remember (not "I am remembered")
- κοιμάμαι = I sleep (not "I am slept")

<etymology>
Why "deponent"? From Latin deponere (to put aside) - these verbs have "set aside" their active forms.
</etymology>

</section>

---

## Start Here: είμαι (to be)

<paradigm name="eimai" highlight="true">
<verb>είμαι</verb>
<meaning>to be</meaning>
<note>The most common Greek verb. Memorize it first. You'll use it in every conversation.</note>
<note>3rd person is the same for singular and plural</note>

| Person       | Singular  | Plural    |
|--------------|-----------|-----------|
| 1st          | είμαι     | είμαστε   |
| 2nd          | είσαι     | είστε     |
| 3rd          | είναι     | είναι     |

</paradigm>

---

## Pattern Power

<insight>
Learn just **3 ending patterns** and you can conjugate thousands of verbs.
The endings tell you WHO is doing the action.
</insight>

<note name="negation">
**Negation:** Add δεν before the verb: Δεν μιλάω (I don't speak)
</note>

---

## Pattern Identifier

<decision-guide name="pattern-identifier">
<question>Which pattern? Look at the verb's dictionary form (1st person singular)</question>

| Ending    | Pattern Name | Examples                |
|-----------|--------------|-------------------------|
| -ω        | Active       | κάνω, θέλω, βλέπω       |
| -άω/-ώ    | Contracted   | μιλάω, αγαπάω, ρωτάω    |
| -μαι      | Deponent     | έρχομαι, θυμάμαι        |

</decision-guide>

---

## Pattern 1: Active -ω

<paradigm name="active" color="ocean">
<pattern>-ω</pattern>
<title>Standard Active</title>
<description>Most Greek verbs follow this pattern. Learn the endings once, apply them to thousands of verbs.</description>

### Canonical: κάνω (do, make)

| Person | Singular      | Plural        |
|--------|---------------|---------------|
| 1st    | κάν**ω**      | κάν**ουμε**   |
| 2nd    | κάν**εις**    | κάν**ετε**    |
| 3rd    | κάν**ει**     | κάν**ουν**    |

### Same Pattern
- θέλω (want)
- έχω (have)
- βλέπω (see)

### In Context
- Τι κάνεις; = How are you? (What do you do?)
- Κάνει κρύο. = It's cold. (It makes cold)
- Κάνουμε διάλειμμα. = We're taking a break.

</paradigm>

---

## Pattern 2: Contracted -άω/-ώ

<paradigm name="contracted" color="terracotta">
<pattern>-άω/-ώ</pattern>
<title>Contracted</title>
<description>The α contracts with endings. Two forms exist - both are correct.</description>

### Canonical: μιλάω (speak)

| Person | Singular      | Plural        |
|--------|---------------|---------------|
| 1st    | μιλ**άω**     | μιλ**άμε**    |
| 2nd    | μιλ**άς**     | μιλ**άτε**    |
| 3rd    | μιλ**άει**    | μιλ**άνε**    |

### Same Pattern
- αγαπάω (love)
- ρωτάω (ask)
- περνάω (pass)

### In Context
- Μιλάς ελληνικά; = Do you speak Greek?
- Δεν μιλάμε πολύ. = We don't speak much.

</paradigm>

---

## Pattern 3: Deponent -μαι

<paradigm name="deponent" color="olive">
<pattern>-μαι</pattern>
<title>Deponent</title>
<description>Look passive but have active meaning. Two sub-patterns: -ομαι and -άμαι.</description>

### Canonical: έρχομαι (come)

| Person | Singular        | Plural          |
|--------|-----------------|-----------------|
| 1st    | έρχ**ομαι**     | ερχ**όμαστε**   |
| 2nd    | έρχ**εσαι**     | έρχ**εστε**     |
| 3rd    | έρχ**εται**     | έρχ**ονται**    |

### Same Pattern
- γίνομαι (become)
- κάθομαι (sit)

### In Context
- Έρχομαι αύριο. = I'm coming tomorrow.
- Πότε έρχεσαι; = When are you coming?
- Δεν θυμάμαι. = I don't remember.

</paradigm>

---

## Other Irregular Verbs

<section name="irregulars">
<note>These common verbs don't follow patterns. You'll learn them naturally through frequent exposure.</note>

### λέω (say, tell)
| Person | Singular | Plural |
|--------|----------|--------|
| 1st    | λέω      | λέμε   |
| 2nd    | λές      | λέτε   |
| 3rd    | λέει     | λένε   |
<note>"τα λέμε" = see you later</note>

### τρώω (eat)
| Person | Singular | Plural |
|--------|----------|--------|
| 1st    | τρώω     | τρώμε  |
| 2nd    | τρώς     | τρώτε  |
| 3rd    | τρώει    | τρώνε  |

### πάω (go)
| Person | Singular | Plural |
|--------|----------|--------|
| 1st    | πάω      | πάμε   |
| 2nd    | πάς      | πάτε   |
| 3rd    | πάει     | πάνε   |
<note>Alternative regular form: πηγαίνω</note>

</section>

