## Past Tense

Greek has two past tenses. Both use the same endings; only the stem changes.

### Aorist vs Imperfect

| Tense     | Think of it as | Example  | English                          |
|-----------|----------------|----------|----------------------------------|
| Aorist    | snapshot       | έγραψα   | I wrote (one completed action)   |
| Imperfect | video          | έγραφα   | I was writing / used to write    |

### Past Endings (shared)

| Person | Singular | Plural |
|--------|----------|--------|
| 1st    | -α       | -αμε   |
| 2nd    | -ες      | -ατε   |
| 3rd    | -ε       | -αν    |

Worked on κάνω: έκανα · έκανες · έκανε · κάναμε · κάνατε · έκαναν

### Aorist Stem Fusion

<decision-guide name="aorist-fusion">
<question>Aorist adds σ to the stem. That σ fuses with the stem's final consonant:</question>

| Stem ends in       | + σ → | Examples                              |
|--------------------|-------|---------------------------------------|
| π / β / φ / ευ     | ψ     | γράφω → έγραψα, κόβω → έκοψα          |
| κ / γ / χ / ζ*     | ξ     | ανοίγω → άνοιξα, αλλάζω → άλλαξα      |
| vowel / ζ*         | σ     | ακούω → άκουσα, διαβάζω → διάβασα     |

</decision-guide>

**Notes:**
- ζ is ambiguous — most -ίζω / -άζω verbs take σ (αγοράζω → αγόρασα), but a few take ξ (αλλάζω → άλλαξα). Memorise per verb.
- -νω verbs don't follow a clean rule — ν drops or mutates unpredictably. They live in the "irregular stems" material.

### The έ- Prefix

Short verbs add an **έ-** so the stress can land two syllables from the end — but it drops when the ending is long enough to carry its own stress:

| With έ-                   | Without έ-        |
|---------------------------|-------------------|
| έγραψα · έγραψες · έγραψε | γράψαμε · γράψατε |

Same for imperfect: έγραφα vs γράφαμε.

### Deponent Aorist (-μαι verbs)

Deponent verbs (those ending -μαι) form the aorist with a **-θηκα** marker — no stem fusion, no σ:

| -μαι → -θηκα              | Variants                    |
|----------------------------|------------------------------|
| λυπάμαι → λυπήθηκα         | χρειάζομαι → χρειά**στ**ηκα (-ζομαι drops ζ)  |
| θυμάμαι → θυμήθηκα         | σκέφτομαι → σκέ**φτ**ηκα (-φτομαι)           |
| φοβάμαι → φοβήθηκα         | χαίρομαι → χάρ**ηκα** (loses -θ-)            |

### Group 2 Aorist (-άω / -ώ verbs)

Contracted verbs form the aorist with a -ησα or -εσα marker — no stem fusion:

| -άω → -ησα            | -ώ → -εσα             |
|------------------------|------------------------|
| μιλάω → μίλησα         | μπορώ → μπόρεσα        |
| ρωτάω → ρώτησα         | οδηγώ → οδήγησα*       |
| αγαπάω → αγάπησα       |                        |

*Some -ώ verbs actually take -ησα — memorise per verb.

### Group 1 Imperfect

For -ω verbs, the imperfect uses the present stem + past endings (no σ fusion):

<paradigm name="g1-imperfect" color="neutral">
<verb>γράφω</verb>
<meaning>write (was writing / used to write)</meaning>

| Person | Singular  | Plural    |
|--------|-----------|-----------|
| 1st    | έγραφα    | γράφαμε   |
| 2nd    | έγραφες   | γράφατε   |
| 3rd    | έγραφε    | έγραφαν   |

</paradigm>

### Group 2 Imperfect

Contracted verbs (μιλάω, αγαπάω) insert -ούσα- before the endings:

<paradigm name="g2-imperfect" color="neutral">
<verb>μιλάω</verb>
<meaning>was speaking / used to speak</meaning>

| Person | Singular    | Plural        |
|--------|-------------|---------------|
| 1st    | μιλούσα     | μιλούσαμε     |
| 2nd    | μιλούσες    | μιλούσατε     |
| 3rd    | μιλούσε     | μιλούσαν      |

</paradigm>

### είμαι · Past (irregular)

<paradigm name="eimai-past" color="olive">
<verb>είμαι</verb>
<meaning>was / were</meaning>
<note>Only an imperfect past exists; no aorist (being is a state, not a completed act)</note>
<note>3rd person is the same for singular and plural</note>

| Person | Singular  | Plural     |
|--------|-----------|------------|
| 1st    | ήμουν     | ήμασταν    |
| 2nd    | ήσουν     | ήσασταν    |
| 3rd    | ήταν      | ήταν       |

</paradigm>

